label chapter12:

    # [Scene: Saltmarsh Fen | Midmorning — First Harvest Day]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Light, hopeful strings — a fragile, stitched-together cheer]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Bees hum, the soft slap of a net being folded, distant gulls]
    "You have spent the spring and summer listening to the marsh. You learned where the reeds choke deep enough to slow a surge, which root-lines hold when mud wants to slide, how oyster clusters knit spores"
    "and silt into something that looks like armor. The grant money rewired old habits into new work: co-op hires who speak local dialects into design meetings, apprentices learning to read the tide not as threat but"
    "as tutor. The harvest is small and honest — salt-tolerant greens, low crowns of winter squash, fragrant rows of sea purslane tossed with lemon and rosemary."
    show tessa_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tessa_kestrel "You were right to make space for the kids' beds. Look at them — the dragonflies think it's a maze."
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "And the kids think it's a kingdom. Both are stubborn, both survive storms better than we expect."
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "You taught them to plant like the marsh speaks. Old ways, new hands — it's working."
    "You taste the salt on the corner of your lips, the harvest's tang bright and immediate. Old Man Rafi leans on a patched rake, eyes wet with a kind of wide, practiced gratitude. He tells a"
    "story about a summer decades past when the marsh was a rumor; people clap once for the memory and once for the future."

    menu:
        "Offer the kids extra purslane to keep them busy":
            "You crowd handfuls of purslane into small, damp palms. A kid giggles, runs off, and your fingers smell like lemon and sea for hours."
        "Walk the outer boardwalk to inspect the new root-mats":
            "You walk the slatted path, knees flexing against the wind. The mats look taut, the stakes holding. For a moment, you allow yourself to believe in slow work."

    # --- merge ---
    "For the day the town breathes easier. People bring folding chairs; someone cooks coffee over a portable burner and the scent threads through the reeds. The boardwalk creaks under friendly weight; laughter ricochets off pilings. You"
    "write notes — measurements, new observations — but mostly you watch. This is the small circumference of joy you fought for: reclaimed soil, community labor, a living buffer that names itself in reeds."
    # [Scene: Research Lighthouse | Late Afternoon]
    hide tessa_kestrel
    hide mira_kestrel
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A low, steady hum — competent, watchful]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant traffic of gulls; the kettle on the small stove whistling once]
    "You go to the lighthouse out of habit and out of duty. Dr. Saira would tell you it's good to check instruments when the sea is warm — currents braid in odd ways over warm water."
    "The data tonight is a whisper at first: slightly elevated sea-surface anomalies, a cluster of warm-core eddies on a satellite feed. When you triangulate against wind shear and late-season baroclinic instability, the numbers slope away from"
    "comfort."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "You saw it?"
    show mira_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "It's forming faster than the models we calibrated for this coast. Not a certainty. A ride on a knife-edge."

    jonah_reyes "Good. Knife-edges are still edges we can walk together."
    "You want to agree differently — you want the wool of optimism — but the instruments hum a different note. You call a few people: Tessa checks moorings, Old Man Rafi tells the kids to bring"
    "extra blankets to the harbor shelter, and neighbors tie the new root-mats tighter where the marsh meets the bay. You order a drone sweep of the inshore soundings; you double-check the co-op crews' shift rotations."

    menu:
        "Stay at the lighthouse to monitor data":
            "You settle into the chair, thumbs twitching across your notebook. The screens build a picture that tightens the pit in your chest; you call the harbor and ask them to double-check lines."
        "Go down to the boardwalk to help secure boats":
            "You grab your field jacket and head down. Hands on wet rope, you smell diesel and tar and the quick metallic fret of fear; neighbors already have their hands on the cleats."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose both, in the end: your legs take you down to the dock and your eyes keep darting back to the lighthouse's beacon where data hangs like a lantern. That afternoon the sky changes faster"
    "than memory — the sun a coin, then a bruise. The wind comes in with a new, insistent syllable."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk & Docks | Early Evening — Storm Onset]
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive strings, insistent and sharp]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The slap of high wind, ropes shrieking against posts, the sudden hollow crash of a loose signboard.]
    "You feel the sky change in the small anatomy of your skin: hairs prickling, an ache behind your molars. The air tastes of copper and ozone. Your notebook is a weight against your ribs though the"
    "pages are full of hope — root-mats, community labor, transparent ledgers. They are full of the right answer, and yet here is a right answer that does not defy gravity."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Tessa — check the north moorings! Rafi — help the left-side pontoons!"
    show tessa_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tessa_kestrel "On it. Mira — the house on Low Street needs sandbags now!"
    show old_man_rafi at center:
        zoom 0.7

    old_man_rafi "Hold fast. Hold the girls' hands. For God's sake, hold fast."
    "Everyone's actions are practiced, rehearsed in drills and during late-night meetings. The co-op teams move like muscle memory: knot, double-knot, stake. You do what you can — you reroute volunteers from the community garden to help"
    "fortify pilings, you check a tide-model one last time. The numbers on your wristband spike. The sea is breathing in a way that asks for more than reeds."
    # [Scene: Saltmarsh Edge | Night — The Surge]
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide tessa_kestrel
    hide old_man_rafi

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Staccato percussion, brass hits; then a swallowed silence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A series of howls and crashes; wood tearing; the long moan of a house frame splitting]
    "Then the compound surge arrives: oceanic swell stacked on atmospheric surge, fed by warm currents. The root-mats hold for a breath and then the water finds seams. Boats that have been cradled by careful hands go"
    "weightless and then frantic, colliding like trapped animals. A line of aging houses on the low side of the boardwalk groans and collapses into foamed ruin, their lights snuffed into a single, angry flicker."
    show mira_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "Jonah!"
    "He's already gone. He steps off a piling into frenzied water to reach a neighbor whose skiff has been torn free. You see him go — a shadow in white spray — and then the ocean"
    "takes its rhythm and his figure is swallowed into it. He does not return quickly enough."
    show tessa_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tessa_kestrel "No — Jonah, come on — come on!"
    show old_man_rafi at center:
        zoom 0.7

    old_man_rafi "No, child — no, no—"
    "Panic is a tissue-thin thing that tears quick. You try to orient the satellite feed from the lighthouse to get a bead on the current; the file buffers and stammers, then streams in jagged lag. Your"
    "data is a corridor of static; instruments report in fractured sentences. The models you built for slow encroachment cannot compress the speed of this compound event. You feel a raw, animal scream rise in you that"
    "is not quite voice."

    mira_kestrel "The models — they're not updating fast enough. We need —"

    tessa_kestrel "We need hands. We need rope. We need him, Mira."
    "There is no time for the rhetoric of righteousness now. There is only the immediate and terrible calculus of bodies and water. You rip a length of line from your pack and throw it toward a"
    "neighbor who is waist-deep, finding the weight of practical things under your fingers. Old Man Rafi collapses to his knees and lets out a sound that detonates the air around you; Tessa fights like a machine"
    "strapped to grief."
    hide mira_kestrel
    hide tessa_kestrel
    hide old_man_rafi

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The roar of the sea; a single gull cry cut short]
    "The community's distributed defenses bought hours, bought places where people could flee, where some lives were saved. They did not buy everything. Houses that should have been reinforced were left in municipal backlog. A fatigue of"
    "funding and bureaucratic slippage had left exposed seams. The fairness of your path — transparency, local stewardship, moral clarity — sits now beside the physics of a storm that does not negotiate."
    # [Scene: Research Lighthouse | Night — Aftermath]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse, descending cello; silence like a held breath]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Muffled sobs, the distant groan of twisted metal, the drip of water from soaked canvas]
    "You stand in the lighthouse with your notebook open, but the pages feel meaningless against the damp and the ruin. Data scrolls in a continuous column — wave heights, current vectors, timestamps — but they are"
    "no longer a map to action so much as a postmortem ledger. You scrub the screen until your hands ache. Numbers explain. Numbers do not cradle."
    show old_man_rafi at left:
        zoom 0.7

    old_man_rafi "I told them the marsh remembers. I told them what it would take. We did what we could, child."
    show tessa_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tessa_kestrel "We did everything we were supposed to do. We followed you, Mira. We trusted the process."
    "You look at Tessa and at Rafi and at the empty stretch where Jonah's boat should be. The absence makes its own geometry: a notch in the night, a place where light didn't catch. You move"
    "toward the door because looking is a way to breathe. On the boardwalk, neighbors haul ruined pontoons like a funeral procession."

    menu:
        "Run back out with the search team":
            "You step into the wet dark with others, lungs burning, calling his name again. Your voice shrieks and cracks; the sea eats it. You push until your muscles refuse, until the cold becomes a separate thing from you."
        "Stay at the lighthouse to coordinate and record everything":
            "You stay, hands steady on the keyboard, calling in assets, pinging for emergency boats. You log every sighting with a lawyerly precision that feels small against the howl outside."

    # --- merge ---
    "Whatever you choose with your steps, nothing snaps the wound closed. Jonah's absence is a pressure that distorts the air. You run; you stay. You do both. Human bodies respond with a dozen tiny certainties: tie, pull, call, log. Each act is an insistence against the sea's taking."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk | Dawn — The Day After]
    hide old_man_rafi
    hide tessa_kestrel

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, low violin note that does not resolve]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant sobs; the wet slap of boots on wood; the slow drip of something down a gutter]
    "Old Man Rafi sits on a sodden log, his hands cupped as if a small animal could be held there and warmed. Tessa stands nearby, sleeves soaked to the elbow, her face a mask of mechanical"
    "motion. People move through the wreckage with the same steady, exhausted care they would bring to a grave. They wrap what can be salvaged; they dig through mud with spoons and bare hands; they chant names"
    "like prayer."
    show mira_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We did the moral thing."
    "The line is not rhetorical. You mean it. The grants were rerouted into co-op wages and seed banks; the marsh has come back in places bright with life where nothing had been. You meant your choices"
    "not as virtue-signals but as stitches in a living system. They did what you asked of them. They did it with love."
    show old_man_rafi at right:
        zoom 0.7

    old_man_rafi "Love does not make the sea smaller."
    "His words land like a wave, immediate and absolute. You have always carried a ledger of what you could not save — the house from your childhood, the dog that went missing in a storm when"
    "you were twelve — and that ledger sits now next to the ledger of this town. The transparency you fought for reads clean on paper; it does not heal what the sea consumes."

    mira_kestrel "Was it enough? Was any of it enough?"
    "The pendant is colder than your skin. The answer is a physics problem and an ethical poem that refuses to resolve. You think of all the mornings you convinced the town to trade short spectacle for"
    "long work, of the faces in meeting rooms who learned to say 'we' instead of 'they.' You think of Jonah's laugh in the light and the way he steadied a nervous apprentice with a palm that"
    "smelled of tar and morning coffee. You think of Tessa's impatient, brilliant hands."
    show tessa_kestrel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    tessa_kestrel "We— we did what we could. He—"
    "The sentence breaks against the horizon. Old Man Rafi makes a small, sudden sound — a cry that is like the unboring of a trench. People begin to name the losses. You write them down because"
    "names become the shape of grief and because a roster is a way to begin repair."
    hide mira_kestrel
    hide old_man_rafi
    hide tessa_kestrel

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The strings thin to a single, unresolved tone; then silence]
    "You sit back on the sodden log beside Old Man Rafi. The salt in the air stings like an accusation and an absolution. Transparency — the thing you demanded, the clean ledger — feels like a"
    "small, adequate salve against a wound that is not meant to be sewn closed by records. It comforts and does not restore. It points at culprits and at systems and at the absence of time when"
    "the storm accelerated beyond planning."
    show mira_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "Can righteous choices outrun the physics of a changing sea?"
    "The question hangs above the fen like a gull unwilling to leave. It is the honest, awful question you have been avoiding because its answer might mean that some losses were never about ethics but about"
    "speed and scale. You feel all the syllables of your life's choices settle into a single, heavy stone at your core."
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_9 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant, hollow boom — the town's old alarm, now a memory]
    "You do not find an answer. There is no tidy moral calculus that will stitch the night back together. Only the work that remains: rebuilding where possible, cataloguing what is beyond repair, teaching children names for the creatures that came back, holding those who cannot be held."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk | Morning — Epilogue Image]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_10 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single low piano note, long and resonant]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Quiet conversation; a child's laugh muffled behind an anxious adult]
    "You sit very still and let the town's noise wash around you. The thing you wanted — a community that governs its own defenses with dignity and care — exists in the bones of what remains."
    "The thing you wanted could not, this day, prevent grief. The two truths are not mutually exclusive. They are, cruelly, both."
    show mira_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_kestrel "We did the moral thing. We will keep doing it."
    "Whether that promise alters the curve of future storms you do not know. You press the cold pendant to your chest once more, feeling its small, stubborn weight. You rise, walk the boardwalk, and begin the inventory — of losses, of supplies, of people who will need shelter and time."
    hide mira_kestrel

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_11 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The piano holds a final low note and fades]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_12 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
